  { question: "What is the half-life of caffeine?", answer: "The average half-life of caffeine in healthy adults is approximately 5 hours. This means that 5 hours after consuming caffeine, half of it remains in your body. After 10 hours, one quarter remains. Individual variation ranges from 3 to 7 hours depending on genetics, liver function, pregnancy, smoking status, and medications." },
  { question: "How is caffeine remaining calculated?", answer: "Caffeine remaining is calculated using the exponential decay formula: C(t) = C0 x (0.5)^(t/5), where C0 is the initial caffeine amount in milligrams, t is the time elapsed in hours, and 5 is the half-life in hours. This produces a smooth decay curve showing how caffeine levels drop over time." },
  { question: "How much caffeine is safe before bed?", answer: "Research suggests that caffeine levels below 50 mg are unlikely to significantly impair sleep for most people. However, caffeine sensitivity varies widely. Some people may need to be below 25 mg, while others can tolerate more. As a general rule, avoid caffeine at least 6-8 hours before bedtime." },
  { question: "How much caffeine is in a cup of coffee?", answer: "An 8-ounce cup of brewed coffee contains approximately 95 mg of caffeine, though this can range from 70 to 140 mg depending on the bean variety and brewing method. An espresso shot contains about 63 mg, black tea about 47 mg, green tea about 28 mg, and a standard energy drink about 80 mg." },
  { question: "What factors affect caffeine metabolism?", answer: "Several factors influence how quickly your body processes caffeine. Smoking increases metabolism by up to 50%. Pregnancy can double the half-life to 10 or more hours. Oral contraceptives can extend it to 5-10 hours. Liver disease significantly slows metabolism. Genetics play a major role through CYP1A2 enzyme variations that determine whether you are a fast or slow caffeine metabolizer." }
]) %>

