    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How the Caffeine Half-Life Calculator Works</h2>
      <p>
        This calculator uses the exponential decay formula C(t) = C0 x (0.5)^(t/5) to model how caffeine is metabolized in your body. The average caffeine half-life in healthy adults is approximately 5 hours, meaning that every 5 hours, the amount of caffeine in your system is reduced by half. Enter the amount of caffeine you consumed, the time you drank it, and your planned bedtime to see exactly how much caffeine will be in your system when you try to sleep.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding caffeine metabolism is crucial for optimizing both your energy levels during the day and your sleep quality at night. Many people underestimate how long caffeine stays active in the body. A cup of coffee consumed at 3 PM will still have about 47 mg of caffeine in your system at 8 PM, and roughly 24 mg at 1 AM. For caffeine-sensitive individuals, even these residual amounts can delay sleep onset and reduce sleep quality.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Caffeine Content in Common Beverages</h2>
      <p>
        An 8-ounce cup of brewed coffee contains approximately 95 mg of caffeine, though this varies from 70 to 140 mg depending on the bean variety and brewing method. A single espresso shot has about 63 mg, black tea provides around 47 mg, and green tea contains approximately 28 mg. Energy drinks typically contain 80 mg per 8 ounces, though larger cans may contain 150 to 300 mg total. Cola sodas have roughly 34 mg per 12-ounce can.
      </p>

      <h2>Factors That Affect Caffeine Half-Life</h2>
      <p>
        While 5 hours is the average, individual caffeine half-life can range from 3 to 7 hours. Smokers metabolize caffeine about 50% faster due to enzyme induction, resulting in a half-life of approximately 3 hours. Pregnancy significantly slows caffeine metabolism, especially in the third trimester when the half-life can extend to 10 to 15 hours. Oral contraceptives can double the half-life. Liver disease and certain medications can also substantially slow caffeine clearance.
      </p>
      <p>
        Genetic variation in the CYP1A2 enzyme, which is responsible for 95% of caffeine metabolism, creates fast and slow metabolizers. Fast metabolizers may have a half-life as short as 2 to 3 hours, while slow metabolizers may take 7 or more hours. This explains why some people can drink coffee late in the day without sleep issues while others are affected by even morning consumption.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the half-life of caffeine?</h3>
      <p>
        The average half-life of caffeine in healthy adults is approximately 5 hours. This means 5 hours after consumption, half of the caffeine remains. After 10 hours, one quarter remains. Individual variation ranges from 3 to 7 hours depending on genetics and other factors.
      </p>

      <h3>How much caffeine is safe before bed?</h3>
      <p>
        Research suggests caffeine levels below 50 mg are unlikely to significantly impair sleep for most people. As a general guideline, avoid caffeine at least 6 to 8 hours before bedtime.
      </p>

      <h3>How much caffeine is in coffee?</h3>
      <p>
        An 8-ounce brewed coffee has about 95 mg, an espresso shot has 63 mg, black tea has 47 mg, green tea has 28 mg, and energy drinks have about 80 mg per 8 ounces.
      </p>

      <h3>What factors speed up caffeine metabolism?</h3>
      <p>
        Smoking increases caffeine metabolism by up to 50%. Regular exercise, being male, and certain genetic variations of CYP1A2 also speed up metabolism.
      </p>

      <h3>Does caffeine build up with multiple cups?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. If you drink a second cup before the first is fully metabolized, the amounts are additive. For example, if you have 95 mg at 8 AM and another 95 mg at 10 AM, at 10 AM you have about 73 mg from the first cup plus 95 mg from the second, totaling roughly 168 mg.
      </p>

